00:00:26.790 --> 00:00:28.650
As usual, I like
to begin by giving

00:00:28.650 --> 00:00:31.040
a review of what we
talked about last time.

00:00:31.040 --> 00:00:34.722
This time on slides instead
of on the blackboard.

00:00:34.722 --> 00:00:36.680
We're talking mainly
about relativistic energy,

00:00:36.680 --> 00:00:39.500
or relativistic energy and
momentum, and pressure,

00:00:39.500 --> 00:00:40.940
sometimes.

00:00:40.940 --> 00:00:44.440
The key equation is probably
the most famous equation

00:00:44.440 --> 00:00:48.220
in physics, Einstein's
e equals m c squared.

00:00:48.220 --> 00:00:49.967
And I gave some
numerical examples.

00:00:49.967 --> 00:00:52.050
I actually looked up some
more numbers since then,

00:00:52.050 --> 00:00:54.037
when I was revising
the lecture notes.

00:00:54.037 --> 00:00:55.620
So these are slightly
more up to date.

00:00:55.620 --> 00:00:59.340
But it's still true that
if you could burn matter

00:00:59.340 --> 00:01:01.840
at the rate of one
kilogram per hour,

00:01:01.840 --> 00:01:04.290
you would have about
one and a half times

00:01:04.290 --> 00:01:06.640
the total power
output of the world.

00:01:06.640 --> 00:01:09.710
And that's apparently
still valid in 2011.

00:01:09.710 --> 00:01:12.620
I only had 2008 figures,
actually, at the lecture

00:01:12.620 --> 00:01:14.950
last time.

00:01:14.950 --> 00:01:18.552
And if you imagine the
15-gallon tank of gasoline,

00:01:18.552 --> 00:01:21.010
and you could figure out how
much that-- what it's mass is,

00:01:21.010 --> 00:01:23.430
and convert that to
energy, it turns out

00:01:23.430 --> 00:01:25.080
that a 15-gallon
tank of gasoline

00:01:25.080 --> 00:01:28.570
could power the world for about
two and half days, if you could

00:01:28.570 --> 00:01:31.130
convert all of it into energy.

00:01:31.130 --> 00:01:34.330
The catch, of course, is
that we can't convert matter

00:01:34.330 --> 00:01:35.710
into energy.

00:01:35.710 --> 00:01:38.930
We can't get around the problem
that, at least at the energies

00:01:38.930 --> 00:01:41.600
that we deal with,
baryon number.

00:01:41.600 --> 00:01:44.280
And that number of protons
and neutrons is conserved,

00:01:44.280 --> 00:01:47.600
so we can't make protons
and neutrons disappear.

00:01:47.600 --> 00:01:50.760
And that means that we're
limited in what we can do.

00:01:50.760 --> 00:01:53.530
In particular, one of the most
efficient things we can do

00:01:53.530 --> 00:01:57.380
is fission uranium 235.

00:01:57.380 --> 00:02:01.170
But when uranium 235 undergoes
fission, less than 1/10

00:02:01.170 --> 00:02:04.100
of 1% of the mass is
actually converted

00:02:04.100 --> 00:02:08.580
into energy, which is why we
can't actually avail ourselves

00:02:08.580 --> 00:02:11.340
of these fantastic
numbers that would apply,

00:02:11.340 --> 00:02:13.690
if we could literally just
convert matter into energy.

00:02:16.410 --> 00:02:20.037
We went on to talk about
the relativistic definitions

00:02:20.037 --> 00:02:22.120
of energy and momentum,
and how they come together

00:02:22.120 --> 00:02:29.190
to form a Lorentz four vector,
and the underlying theme here

00:02:29.190 --> 00:02:32.580
is that we consider ourselves
users of special relativity.

00:02:32.580 --> 00:02:35.720
Most of you I know have taken
special relativity courses,

00:02:35.720 --> 00:02:39.370
and for those of you who
have, this is a review.

00:02:39.370 --> 00:02:41.820
For those you who have not,
and there are some of those

00:02:41.820 --> 00:02:45.070
also, no need to panic.

00:02:45.070 --> 00:02:47.700
I intend to tell you
every fact that you

00:02:47.700 --> 00:02:49.740
need to know about
special relativity.

00:02:49.740 --> 00:02:52.110
I won't tell you how
to derive them all,

00:02:52.110 --> 00:02:55.890
but I'll tell you all you'll
need to know for this class.

00:02:55.890 --> 00:02:57.830
So in particular, it's
useful for this class

00:02:57.830 --> 00:03:00.780
to recognize that energy and
momentum can be put together

00:03:00.780 --> 00:03:04.850
into a four vector, where
the zeroth component

00:03:04.850 --> 00:03:07.450
is the energy divided
by the speed of light.

00:03:07.450 --> 00:03:11.590
And the three spatial components
are just the three components

00:03:11.590 --> 00:03:13.490
of the spatial
momentum, although they

00:03:13.490 --> 00:03:16.400
have to be defined
relativistically.

00:03:16.400 --> 00:03:18.360
The relativistic
definition of momentum,

00:03:18.360 --> 00:03:20.430
at least how it
relates to velocity,

00:03:20.430 --> 00:03:22.440
is that it's equal to
gamma times the rest

00:03:22.440 --> 00:03:26.459
mass times the velocity, where
gamma is the famous factor

00:03:26.459 --> 00:03:28.000
that we've been
seeing all along when

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:30.080
we've talked about relativity.

00:03:30.080 --> 00:03:32.360
The Lorentz
contraction factor, one

00:03:32.360 --> 00:03:36.180
over the square root of 1
minus v squared over c squared.

00:03:36.180 --> 00:03:38.080
The energy of a particle,
relativistically,

00:03:38.080 --> 00:03:41.750
is the same gamma, times m
0 times c squared, and it

00:03:41.750 --> 00:03:44.370
can also be written as
the square root of m 0

00:03:44.370 --> 00:03:46.970
c squared squared, plus
the momentum squared,

00:03:46.970 --> 00:03:50.090
times c squared.

00:03:50.090 --> 00:03:52.360
Since the momentum
forms a four vector,

00:03:52.360 --> 00:03:57.780
its Lorentz and variant square
should be Lorentz and variant,

00:03:57.780 --> 00:03:59.970
and that means that
the momentum squared

00:03:59.970 --> 00:04:04.300
minus p 0 squared should be the
same in all inertial reference

00:04:04.300 --> 00:04:05.650
frames.

00:04:05.650 --> 00:04:07.230
And that's just
equal when you put

00:04:07.230 --> 00:04:09.600
in what p 0 means,
the momentum squared

00:04:09.600 --> 00:04:12.530
minus the energy squared,
divided by c 0 squared.

00:04:12.530 --> 00:04:15.030
And to know what value it's
equal to in all frames,

00:04:15.030 --> 00:04:18.564
it's efficient to know what
it's equal to in one frame.

00:04:18.564 --> 00:04:19.980
And the one frame
where we do know

00:04:19.980 --> 00:04:22.870
what it's equal to is the
rest frame of a particle.

00:04:22.870 --> 00:04:25.160
So in the rest frame,
the momentum vanishes,

00:04:25.160 --> 00:04:28.039
and the energy is
just m 0 c squared.

00:04:28.039 --> 00:04:29.830
So in the rest frame,
we can evaluate this,

00:04:29.830 --> 00:04:34.310
and we get minus m
0 c squared squared.

00:04:34.310 --> 00:04:36.880
And that means that has to
be the value in every frame.

00:04:36.880 --> 00:04:39.280
And this in fact is
the easy way to derive

00:04:39.280 --> 00:04:41.450
the relationship between
energy and momentum.

00:04:41.450 --> 00:04:44.310
If we go back, the
equation we had

00:04:44.310 --> 00:04:49.210
relating energy and momentum is
really exactly that equation,

00:04:49.210 --> 00:04:49.710
rearranged.

00:04:52.850 --> 00:04:55.490
Just to give an example of how
this works, when we actually

00:04:55.490 --> 00:04:58.040
have energy exchanges,
I pointed out

00:04:58.040 --> 00:05:00.900
that we could talk about the
energy of a hydrogen atom.

00:05:00.900 --> 00:05:04.250
And because energy and
mass are equivalent,

00:05:04.250 --> 00:05:07.550
the hydrogen atom clearly
has a little bit less energy

00:05:07.550 --> 00:05:11.020
than an isolated proton,
plus an isolated electron.

00:05:11.020 --> 00:05:12.520
Because when you
bring them together

00:05:12.520 --> 00:05:14.880
there's a binding energy,
and that binding energy

00:05:14.880 --> 00:05:19.350
is called delta e, and has
a value of 13.6 electron

00:05:19.350 --> 00:05:22.290
volts for the ground
state of hydrogen.

00:05:22.290 --> 00:05:24.290
So that tells us the
mass of an hydrogen atom

00:05:24.290 --> 00:05:26.130
is not the sum of
the two masses,

00:05:26.130 --> 00:05:28.150
but rather has this
correction factor,

00:05:28.150 --> 00:05:32.564
because we've taken out a little
bit of energy for the binding.

00:05:32.564 --> 00:05:34.730
And that means we've taken
out a little bit of mass.

00:05:39.010 --> 00:05:42.125
OK, then we talked about the
mass density of radiation

00:05:42.125 --> 00:05:46.040
and how-- building up to how
that will affect the universe.

00:05:46.040 --> 00:05:49.280
And we said that the
mass density of radiation

00:05:49.280 --> 00:05:52.710
is just the energy density
divided by c squared.

00:05:52.710 --> 00:05:55.240
And that can be taken, really,
as a definition of what

00:05:55.240 --> 00:05:58.040
we call relativistic
mass, and hence

00:05:58.040 --> 00:06:01.070
relativistic mass density.

00:06:01.070 --> 00:06:03.750
But the important point is
that this mass density actually

00:06:03.750 --> 00:06:06.590
does gravitate the
same as any other mass

00:06:06.590 --> 00:06:08.380
density of the same value.

00:06:08.380 --> 00:06:12.490
It really does create
gravity in the same way.

00:06:12.490 --> 00:06:15.390
Now I mentioned that things are
much more complicated if you

00:06:15.390 --> 00:06:18.580
want to talk about the
gravitational field produced

00:06:18.580 --> 00:06:20.520
by a single moving particle.

00:06:20.520 --> 00:06:22.990
That's asymmetric, the
velocity of the particle

00:06:22.990 --> 00:06:27.720
shows up in the equations that
describe the metric surrounding

00:06:27.720 --> 00:06:29.570
a single moving particle.

00:06:29.570 --> 00:06:32.280
But if you have a gas
of particles moving

00:06:32.280 --> 00:06:35.270
at high velocities, where
the velocities nonetheless

00:06:35.270 --> 00:06:38.850
average to zero, which
tends to happen, in a gas

00:06:38.850 --> 00:06:42.290
at least in the rest
frame of the gas.

00:06:42.290 --> 00:06:46.810
Then that gas will produce
gravitational fields,

00:06:46.810 --> 00:06:49.650
just like a static mass density.

00:06:49.650 --> 00:06:53.430
Where the mass density is this
relativistic energy divided

00:06:53.430 --> 00:06:59.010
by c squared, the relativistic
definition of the mass density.

00:06:59.010 --> 00:07:03.260
It's also useful to know
that the photon-- if we want

00:07:03.260 --> 00:07:07.280
to describe it as a particle,
is a particle of zero rest mass.

00:07:07.280 --> 00:07:09.430
Which means that it
can never be at rest,

00:07:09.430 --> 00:07:11.350
it always moves at
the speed of light.

00:07:11.350 --> 00:07:15.030
And it also means that its
energy can be arbitrarily

00:07:15.030 --> 00:07:19.970
small, because the energy
is proportional of momentum,

00:07:19.970 --> 00:07:24.049
and the momentum of a photon
can be as small as you like.

00:07:24.049 --> 00:07:26.340
For giving frequency, of
course, the energy of a photon

00:07:26.340 --> 00:07:27.570
is fixed.

00:07:27.570 --> 00:07:30.820
It's h times nu but
if you're allowed

00:07:30.820 --> 00:07:34.270
to vary the frequency,
which you can do if you just

00:07:34.270 --> 00:07:36.450
look at it in
different frames, you

00:07:36.450 --> 00:07:39.710
can make the energy
as small as you like.

00:07:39.710 --> 00:07:42.099
And the famous equation
then, p squared minus e

00:07:42.099 --> 00:07:44.140
squared c squared, which
would have on the right,

00:07:44.140 --> 00:07:48.370
minus m 0 squared
c to the 4th m 0

00:07:48.370 --> 00:07:51.280
squared c squared, excuse me--
has zero on the right hand

00:07:51.280 --> 00:07:54.070
side, because m 0
is 0 And that means

00:07:54.070 --> 00:07:58.230
that for photons, the energy is
just the speed of light times

00:07:58.230 --> 00:07:59.220
the momentum.

00:07:59.220 --> 00:08:01.790
And that's a famous
relationship that photons obey.

00:08:06.200 --> 00:08:09.310
Now, thinking about
how this gas of photons

00:08:09.310 --> 00:08:15.400
will behave in the universe,
we realized immediately

00:08:15.400 --> 00:08:17.360
that it does not
behave the same way

00:08:17.360 --> 00:08:21.760
as a mass density of ordinary
non-relativistic particles.

00:08:21.760 --> 00:08:24.202
Which is what we have
been dealing with to date.

00:08:24.202 --> 00:08:27.180
The important difference
is that in both cases,

00:08:27.180 --> 00:08:30.370
the number density falls
off like 1 over a cubed,

00:08:30.370 --> 00:08:33.190
as the universe expands,
these particles are not

00:08:33.190 --> 00:08:35.159
created and destroyed
in significant numbers,

00:08:35.159 --> 00:08:37.700
they just persevere.

00:08:37.700 --> 00:08:40.690
So the number density of either
non-relativistic particles,

00:08:40.690 --> 00:08:44.470
or photons, just falls off
like one over the volume,

00:08:44.470 --> 00:08:48.950
as the volume increases and
the number density dilutes.

00:08:48.950 --> 00:08:52.380
But what makes photons
different from non-relativistic

00:08:52.380 --> 00:08:55.350
particles, is that a
non-relativistic particle

00:08:55.350 --> 00:08:57.650
will maintain the
energy of that particle

00:08:57.650 --> 00:09:00.200
as the universe
expands, but photons

00:09:00.200 --> 00:09:02.350
will redshift as the
universe expands.

00:09:02.350 --> 00:09:05.200
So each photon will
itself lose energy.

00:09:05.200 --> 00:09:09.070
And it loses energy proportional
to one over the scale factor.

00:09:09.070 --> 00:09:12.820
And that's just because the
frequency shift proportionally

00:09:12.820 --> 00:09:15.220
to the scale factor.

00:09:15.220 --> 00:09:17.390
And that means that
the energy per photon

00:09:17.390 --> 00:09:19.720
shifts, because
quantum mechanically

00:09:19.720 --> 00:09:21.710
we know that the
energy of a photon

00:09:21.710 --> 00:09:23.920
is proportional
to its frequency.

00:09:23.920 --> 00:09:27.000
So if the frequency
redshifts so must the energy.

00:09:27.000 --> 00:09:30.250
In exactly the same
way, 1 over a f t.

00:09:30.250 --> 00:09:31.416
Yes, question?

00:09:31.416 --> 00:09:34.890
AUDIENCE: You said
previously that neutrinos

00:09:34.890 --> 00:09:36.730
behave like radiation
in the sense

00:09:36.730 --> 00:09:39.810
that theta energy
falls is 1 over a.

00:09:39.810 --> 00:09:43.472
What is it about them
that makes this happen?

00:09:43.472 --> 00:09:47.452
Because there are also particles
with standard kinetic energy,

00:09:47.452 --> 00:09:48.077
right?

00:09:48.077 --> 00:09:50.410
PROFESSOR: OK, the question,
in case you didn't hear it,

00:09:50.410 --> 00:09:54.100
is why-- how did
neutrinos fit in here?

00:09:54.100 --> 00:09:56.520
I've made the claim that
neutrinos act like radiation

00:09:56.520 --> 00:09:59.820
in the early universe, but
neutrinos have a non-zero mass,

00:09:59.820 --> 00:10:02.630
so they should obey the
standard formulas for particles

00:10:02.630 --> 00:10:04.440
with nonzero masses.

00:10:04.440 --> 00:10:06.590
The answer to that
is-- there is,

00:10:06.590 --> 00:10:08.730
I think, a simple answer,
which is that as long

00:10:08.730 --> 00:10:12.760
as the energy is large
compared to the mass,

00:10:12.760 --> 00:10:16.480
particles with masses will still
act like massless particles.

00:10:16.480 --> 00:10:19.430
It doesn't really matter
if the mass is zero or not,

00:10:19.430 --> 00:10:23.979
the key thing, really,
is this equation.

00:10:23.979 --> 00:10:25.520
So if the term on
the right hand side

00:10:25.520 --> 00:10:28.270
is small compared to either
of the two on the left,

00:10:28.270 --> 00:10:30.360
it's not much different
from being zero.

00:10:30.360 --> 00:10:32.120
And that's what
happens for neutrinos

00:10:32.120 --> 00:10:33.740
in the early universe.

00:10:33.740 --> 00:10:36.470
And we'll see soon that if
you go to early enough times,

00:10:36.470 --> 00:10:39.300
it's true even for
electron-positron pairs.

00:10:39.300 --> 00:10:41.960
They will also act
like radiation.

00:10:41.960 --> 00:10:43.930
Any particle will
act like radiation

00:10:43.930 --> 00:10:47.390
as long as the energy is large
compared to the rest energy.

00:10:51.130 --> 00:10:53.530
So getting back
to the discussion

00:10:53.530 --> 00:10:57.340
of the early universe, if
the energy of each photon

00:10:57.340 --> 00:10:59.396
falls off like one
over the scale factor,

00:10:59.396 --> 00:11:02.020
and the number density falls off
like one over the scale factor

00:11:02.020 --> 00:11:04.315
cubed, it means that
the energy density,

00:11:04.315 --> 00:11:07.580
and hence, the mass
density of radiation

00:11:07.580 --> 00:11:10.540
will fall off like one
over a to the fourth,

00:11:10.540 --> 00:11:14.270
in contrast to the one over
a cubed, that we found when

00:11:14.270 --> 00:11:17.015
we were talking about
non-relativistic matter.

00:11:17.015 --> 00:11:19.140
And that, of course, is
going to make a difference.

00:11:19.140 --> 00:11:23.119
Because those issues play a
key role in our discussions

00:11:23.119 --> 00:11:24.410
about how the universe evolved.

00:11:28.080 --> 00:11:30.400
An important feature,
which we see immediately,

00:11:30.400 --> 00:11:35.760
is that if we extrapolate
backwards in time,

00:11:35.760 --> 00:11:39.050
since the radiation mass density
is falling off like one over a

00:11:39.050 --> 00:11:41.980
to the fourth, and the
matter density is falling off

00:11:41.980 --> 00:11:44.960
like one over a cubed, it means
that as you go back in time,

00:11:44.960 --> 00:11:46.990
the radiation becomes
more and more important

00:11:46.990 --> 00:11:52.020
relative to the matter, by
factor of the scale factor.

00:11:52.020 --> 00:11:54.190
So if we go back far
enough, we will even

00:11:54.190 --> 00:11:57.910
find a time when the
mass density in radiation

00:11:57.910 --> 00:12:00.700
equaled the mass density
in non-relativistic matter.

00:12:00.700 --> 00:12:03.490
And we calculated about
when that would be.

00:12:03.490 --> 00:12:08.030
We said that the energy
density in radiation today

00:12:08.030 --> 00:12:11.650
is given by this number, 7
times 10 to the minus 14,

00:12:11.650 --> 00:12:12.737
joules per meter cubed.

00:12:12.737 --> 00:12:15.070
And I just gave you this
number, I didn't derive it yet.

00:12:15.070 --> 00:12:17.800
We will derive it,
probably later today.

00:12:17.800 --> 00:12:20.010
But for now, we're
just accepting it.

00:12:20.010 --> 00:12:22.310
And that implies
we can calculate

00:12:22.310 --> 00:12:24.060
from that the ratio
of the mass densities

00:12:24.060 --> 00:12:26.800
in radiation and
ordinary matter.

00:12:26.800 --> 00:12:29.520
Here, we use the fact
that ordinary matter

00:12:29.520 --> 00:12:31.750
can be described
by having an omega

00:12:31.750 --> 00:12:34.697
ratio to the critical
density of about 0.3.

00:12:34.697 --> 00:12:36.780
And we know how to calculate
the critical density,

00:12:36.780 --> 00:12:40.420
and that allowed us to calculate
the density of ordinary matter.

00:12:40.420 --> 00:12:44.160
And then this ratio turned
out to be 3.1 times 10

00:12:44.160 --> 00:12:45.980
to the minus four.

00:12:45.980 --> 00:12:48.740
So radiation in
today's universe is

00:12:48.740 --> 00:12:51.000
almost negligible
in its contribution

00:12:51.000 --> 00:12:53.220
to the overall energy
balance, compared

00:12:53.220 --> 00:12:55.910
to non-relativistic matter.

00:12:55.910 --> 00:12:58.730
But if you
extrapolate backwards,

00:12:58.730 --> 00:13:01.800
we know that this ratio will
vary as one over the scale

00:13:01.800 --> 00:13:02.837
factor.

00:13:02.837 --> 00:13:04.420
And we could figure
out what constants

